1829338074, "span": {"begin": 526, "end": 530}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "intraepithelial lymphocytes", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7267589569091797, "span": {"begin": 686, "end": 713}}, {"id": ["CL:0000803"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IEL", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.9177337884902954, "span": {"begin": 715, "end": 718}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3600"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-15", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9917443990707397, "span": {"begin": 870, "end": 875}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "enterocytes", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7493441104888916, "span": {"begin": 883, "end": 894}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3107"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "non-classical MHC molecules", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9629228711128235, "span": {"begin": 946, "end": 973}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IELs", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8814349174499512, "span": {"begin": 1024, "end": 1028}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013121"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "flattening", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9529452919960022, "span": {"begin": 1086, "end": 1096}}], "text": "The activation of adaptive T and B cell responses to gluten due to loss of mucosal tolerance results in inflammation in the lamina propria of the upper small intestine characterized by a highly significant increase in the presence of both innate and adaptive immune cells. This is accompanied by a highly significant upregulation of the expression of HLA-class II molecules, the production of immune stimulatory and pro-inflammatory cytokines, including IFN-&gamma;, TNF-&alpha;, IL-2, IL-7, and IL-21, by the gluten-reactive CD4+ T cells (Santos et al., 2024;De Nitto et al., 2009; Garrote et al., 2008). In addition, there is a massive increase in the number and activation status of intraepithelial lymphocytes (IEL) in the intestinal epithelium, likely driven by a combination of the pro-inflammatory cytokines produced in the lamina propria and local production of IL-15 by the enterocytes (Abadie et al., 2020). Moreover, the expression of non-classical MHC molecules is upregulated in the epithelium. These activated IELs mediate epithelial cell destruction, contributing to the flattening of the intestinal villi and leading to loss of barrier function (Abadie et al., 2012).     &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:11:19 +0000 2026"}